
@node SBCL Build Process
@chapter SBCL Build Process

The entry point to the bulid process is @file{make.sh} which calls the
following scripts directly and in order:

@table @file
@item make-config.sh 
@item make-host-1.sh
@item make-target-1.sh
@item make-host-2.sh
@item make-target-2.sh
@item make-target-contrib.sh
@end table

@sp
@noindent
The shell script files in turn load lisp files, sometimes with
analogous names, e.g. @file{make-host-1.sh} @arrow{}
@file{make-host-1.lisp}. The lisp files behave in a very similar way
to the conventions of shell scripts, i.e. the loading of the file
creates side effects and many functions are defined at the top of the
file and then called at the top level futher in the file. Because the
files are only loaded once, there are no @code{eval-when}s. The
context is always assumed to be @code{:load-toplevel}. It should also
be noted that a single lisp session is not mainted throughout. In
particular each shell scripts terminates any CL sessions it it
initiated when it ends. The following is an example of the convention:

@example
echo '(load "loader.lisp") (load-sbcl-file "make-host-1.lisp")' | \
    $SBCL_XC_HOST
@end example


@node make-config.sh
@section @file {make-config.sh}
@cindex make-config.sh

@file{make-configu.sh} is called like the following:

@command{sh make-config.sh --xc-host="sbcl" --arch=riscv64 --check-host-lisp}

@sp
@noindent
This creates the @file{output/} directory that ordinarily contains the
following files (and a few additional ones for Android):

@table @file
@item build-config

This sets up shell environment variables: @env{GNUMAKE},
@env{SBCL_XC_HOST}, @env{android}, @env{SBCL_CONTRIB_BLOCKLIST}, and
@env{SBCL_HOST_LOCATION} (for rsync).

@item build-id.inc
This creates a string to designate the build, something like:
@code{my-host-userid-2026-01-01-11-00-00}. I.e. A compbination of
host, user id, date and time.

@item dynamic-space-size.txt

Used to communicate the @code{--dynamic-space-size} parameter to
lisp, i.e., in @file{src/compiler/generic/parms.lisp}

@example
(with-open-file (f "output/dynamic-space-size.txt"
                   :if-does-not-exist nil)
    @dots{})
@end example

@item prefix.def
This is contains the prefix to which SBCL will be install using the
@file{install.sh} command, e.g. @code{SBCL_PREFIX='/usr/local'}


@end table


Further in the build process additional files will also be added to
this directory. If you're performing an android cross-compile build,
additional files like, @file{output/ndk-config} will also be added
during @file{make-config.sh}.

In addition to @file{output/}, @file{make-config.sh} also create
@file{local-target-features.lisp-expr}, the basic lisp parameters for
the build. It is primarily used by @file{shared.lisp}. It looks
something like the following lambda expression:

@example
;;;; This is a machine-generated file.
;;;; Please do not edit it by hand.
;;;; See make-config.sh.
(lambda (features)
  (set-difference
   (union features
          (list :riscv
                :sb-thread
                :os-provides-clock-gettime
                :unix
                :linux
                :elf
                :64-bit
                :little-endian
                :os-provides-dlopen
                :os-provides-dladdr
                :os-provides-blksize-t
                :os-provides-suseconds-t
                :os-provides-getprotoby-r
                :os-provides-poll
                :os-provides-close-range-wrapper
                :os-provides-posix-spawn
                :gencgc
                :compare-and-swap-vops
                :memory-barrier-vops))
   (list)))
@end example
The individual keyword elements are built up using a fairly elaborate
(and perhaps not very robust), network of shell script conditionals,
e.g.

@example
case "$sbcl_os" in
    linux)
        printf ' :unix :linux :elf' >> $ltf
        case "$sbcl_arch" in
          arm64 | ppc64 | x86 | x86-64)
	        printf ' :gcc-tls' >> $ltf
        esac
        case "$sbcl_arch" in
          arm | arm64 | ppc | ppc64 | x86 | x86-64)
	        printf ' :use-sys-mmap' >> $ltf
        esac
        @dots{}
@end example
@noindent
where @code{$ltf} is the @file{local-target-features.lisp-expr} file.

@sp
@noindent
@file{make-config.sh} is also rsync aware. So, if you've specified the
@code{--host-location} flag, it will try and rsync to the specified host.


@example
if [ -n "$SBCL_HOST_LOCATION" ]; then
    echo //setting up host configuration
    rsync --delete-after -a output/ "$SBCL_HOST_LOCATION/output/"
    rsync -a local-target-features.lisp-expr version.lisp-expr \
        "$SBCL_HOST_LOCATION/"
fi
@end example



If you're cross-compiling, @file{make-config.sh} should "do the right
thing" when run on the target machine, with the minor caveat that any
@file{--xc-host} parameter should be suitable for the host machine
instead of the target.


@node make-host-1.sh
@section @file {make-host-1.sh}
@cindex make-host-1.sh

@file{make-host-1.sh} Is called by @file{make.sh} with no parameters,
getting its configuration from @file{local-target-features.lisp-expr}
read by @file{shared.lisp}. The file is a thin wrapper to
@file{make-host-1.lisp}. It compiles and loads the cross-compiler. The
cross compiler is not actually run until @file{make-host-2.sh} But
needs to be loaded because each file has potential dependancies on
previous files.


The lisp file, @file{make-host-1.lisp}, is mostly loaded for its side
effects. The following exposition outlines it's behavior.

